\chapter{Command-Line Interface}

The CLI glues the earlier modules together.  It is intentionally thin: the real
behaviour lives in the store, server, and LaTeX helpers, while the command line
mainly resolves configuration defaults and presents the results in formats that
fit a terminal.

<<[[cli.py]]>>=
from __future__ import annotations

<<imports>>

<<constants>>
<<functions>>
<<cli setup>>
@

The imports show the CLI's intended role.  It depends on Typer for argument
parsing, on the lower-level modules for behaviour, and on a few standard
library modules for terminal formatting and serialisation.  Keeping those
concerns in the imported modules is what lets the command functions below stay
mostly as wiring.

