\section{Shared command helpers}

The first helper family centralises configuration defaults.  Command functions
should not have to remember how missing [[--store]], [[--port]], or
[[--base-url]] values map onto persisted settings; they should only decide
which explicit command-line value, if any, takes precedence.

<<functions>>=
def _configured_store(path: str | None) -> Store:
    return Store(path or get_setting(STORE_CONFIG, DEFAULT_STORE_PATH))


def _configured_port(port: int | None) -> int:
    return int(port or get_setting(PORT_CONFIG, DEFAULT_PORT))


def _configured_base(base: str | None) -> str | None:
    if base is not None:
        return base
    return get_setting(BASE_URL_CONFIG)
@

The render subcommands all expose the same layout, URL, QR, and store options.
Collecting those keyword arguments in one helper keeps the individual command
bodies focused on constructing the right question kind rather than duplicating
the shared registration/rendering policy.

<<functions>>=
def _render_common_kwargs(
    *,
    store: str | None,
    environment: str | None,
    show_url: bool | None,
    base_url: str | None,
    qr_dir: str | None,
    qr_format: str | None,
    layout: str,
) -> dict:
    return {
        "store": _configured_store(store),
        "environment": environment,
        "show_url": show_url,
        "base_url": base_url,
        "qr_dir": qr_dir,
        "qr_format": qr_format,
        "layout": layout,
    }
@

URL commands accept any stored prefix or full hash, but they should always
print the canonical issued prefix.  The resolver therefore first asks the store
for an exact issued prefix, then reports ambiguous partial matches as CLI input
errors instead of guessing.

<<functions>>=
def _join_url(base_url: str, prefix: str) -> str:
    return f"{base_url.rstrip('/')}/{prefix}"


def _resolve_full_hash(store: Store, prefix: str) -> str:
    full_hash = store.resolve(prefix)
    if full_hash is not None:
        return full_hash

    matches = store.matches(prefix)
    if len(matches) > 1:
        raise typer.BadParameter(f"{prefix!r} matches multiple questions")
    raise typer.BadParameter(f"{prefix!r} does not match any question")


def _canonical_prefix(store: Store, prefix: str) -> str:
    full_hash = _resolve_full_hash(store, prefix)
    return store.metadata(full_hash)["url_prefix"]
@

Terminal output needs small presentation helpers.  Values from configuration
may be strings, numbers, booleans, or [[None]], so JSON is the safest fallback
representation; question text is collapsed to a single line before truncation
or wrapping so stored newlines do not break the table layout.

<<functions>>=
def _format_value(value) -> str:
    if isinstance(value, str):
        return value
    return json.dumps(value, ensure_ascii=False)


def _single_line_text(text: str) -> str:
    return " ".join(text.split())


def _question_summary(text: str) -> str:
    text = _single_line_text(text)
    if len(text) <= LIST_PREVIEW_WIDTH:
        return text
    return text[: LIST_PREVIEW_WIDTH - 3] + "..."


def _terminal_width() -> int:
    return shutil.get_terminal_size((LIST_FALLBACK_WIDTH, 24)).columns
@

Open answers often use Markdown for emphasis, lists, and fenced code blocks.
They must reach Rich as renderables rather than as pre-rendered strings;
otherwise terminal colour and syntax highlighting are lost before [[view]] or
[[watch]] can print them.

<<functions>>=
def _result_console() -> Console:
    return Console(width=_terminal_width())
@

The default listing optimises for scanning: prefix first, short preview second.
The [[--full]] variant spends the available terminal width on wrapped question
text while preserving a fixed prefix column, so long questions remain readable
without hiding the URL token lecturers need.

<<functions>>=
def _question_listing(entries: list[dict[str, object]], *, full: bool) -> str:
    if not entries:
        return "No questions registered yet."

    if not full:
        return "\n".join(
            f'{entry["url_prefix"]}  {_question_summary(str(entry["text"]))}'
            for entry in entries
        )

    prefix_width = max(len(str(entry["url_prefix"])) for entry in entries)
    text_width = max(
        LIST_MIN_TEXT_WIDTH,
        _terminal_width() - prefix_width - LIST_COLUMN_GAP,
    )
    lines = []

    for entry in entries:
        prefix = str(entry["url_prefix"])
        wrapped = textwrap.wrap(
            _single_line_text(str(entry["text"])),
            width=text_width,
            break_long_words=False,
            break_on_hyphens=False,
        ) or [""]
        lines.append(
            f"{prefix:<{prefix_width}}{' ' * LIST_COLUMN_GAP}{wrapped[0]}"
        )
        indent = " " * (prefix_width + LIST_COLUMN_GAP)
        for line in wrapped[1:]:
            lines.append(f"{indent}{line}")

    return "\n".join(lines)
@

The terminal bar chart is the same visualisation as the HTML results page: one
row per category, a bar proportional to the relative count, and a numeric count
with its rounded percentage.  The layout reserves space for the bar and count
first, then shortens overlong labels if needed, so a long option cannot squeeze
the visualisation itself out of the terminal.

<<functions>>=
def _render_terminal_bar_chart(
    labels: list[str],
    counts: list[int],
    percentages: list[float],
    *,
    console: Console,
):
    count_texts = [
        f"{count} ({percentage:.0f}%)"
        for count, percentage in zip(counts, percentages)
    ]
    count_width = max((len(text) for text in count_texts), default=0)
    available = max(console.width - count_width - 4, 2)
    max_label_width = max(
        (len(_single_line_text(str(label))) for label in labels),
        default=1,
    )
    label_width = min(max_label_width, max(1, available - TERMINAL_BAR_MIN_WIDTH))
    bar_width = max(1, available - label_width)

    table = Table.grid(padding=(0, 2))
    table.add_column(width=label_width, no_wrap=True)
    table.add_column(width=bar_width, no_wrap=True)
    table.add_column(width=count_width, justify="right", no_wrap=True)

    for label, percentage, count_text in zip(labels, percentages, count_texts):
        shown_label = _single_line_text(str(label))
        if len(shown_label) > label_width:
            if label_width > 3:
                shown_label = shown_label[: label_width - 3] + "..."
            else:
                shown_label = shown_label[:label_width]

        table.add_row(
            shown_label,
            Bar(
                TERMINAL_BAR_SIZE,
                0,
                percentage,
                width=bar_width,
                color="cyan",
                bgcolor="grey23",
            ),
            count_text,
        )

    console.print(table)
@

The alignment test uses one long and one short label because that is where a
plain string layout most easily drifts.  The first non-ASCII character in each
row is the block bar, so equal positions mean the plot area is aligned.

<<test functions>>=
def test_terminal_bar_chart_aligns_short_and_long_labels():
    buffer = io.StringIO()
    console = Console(
        file=buffer,
        force_terminal=False,
        color_system=None,
        width=80,
    )

    mentipy.cli._render_terminal_bar_chart(
        ["Short", "A much longer label"],
        [1, 3],
        [25.0, 75.0],
        console=console,
    )

    lines = buffer.getvalue().splitlines()
    bar_starts = [
        re.search(r"[^\x00-\x7f]", line).start()
        for line in lines
    ]
    assert len(set(bar_starts)) == 1
    assert lines[0].index("1 (25%)") == lines[1].index("3 (75%)")
@

